I"«<p>In Fall 2020, I took a course on Swarms and Multi-Robot Systems. As a part of this course, we had small projects to implement some of the swarm behaviors studied in class on simulated robots. The projects are summarized below.</p>

<h1 id="project-1-leader-follower">Project 1: Leader-Follower</h1>

<p>The goal of this project is to have one robot orbit another robot. The orbiting robot should orbit in clockwise direction, the color of both robots should show distance error (green if less than desired distance, red otherwise), and don‚Äôt assume the other robot is stationary!</p>

<iframe width="389" height="382.5" src="https://www.youtube.com/embed/71MvbdRpeF0" title="YouTube video player" frameborder="0" allow="accelerometer; autoplay; clipboard-write; encrypted-media; gyroscope; picture-in-picture" allowfullscreen=""></iframe>

<h1 id="project-2-hopcount">Project 2: Hopcount</h1>

<p>This project implemented the coordinate system based on hopcount based on the paper ‚ÄúOrganizing a global coordinate system from local information on an ad hoc sensor network.‚Äù The goal was to display the Northwestern ‚ÄúN‚Äù with 256 robots by adjusting the robot‚Äôs color (no robot motion). For this project, I implemented both the ‚Äústandard‚Äù and the ‚Äúsmoothing‚Äù approaches to coordinates from the paper.</p>

<p>This video shows a ‚Äústandard‚Äù implementation based on coordinates.</p>
<iframe width="389" height="382.5" src="https://www.youtube.com/embed/1wXhJf3BgZ" title="YouTube video player" frameborder="0" allow="accelerometer; autoplay; clipboard-write; encrypted-media; gyroscope; picture-in-picture" allowfullscreen=""></iframe>

<p>This video shows a ‚Äúsmooth‚Äù implementation based on coordinates.</p>
<iframe width="389" height="382.5" src="https://www.youtube.com/embed/YERqq1f1-po" title="YouTube video player" frameborder="0" allow="accelerometer; autoplay; clipboard-write; encrypted-media; gyroscope; picture-in-picture" allowfullscreen=""></iframe>

